### 3. **Implementation Phase**

#### 3.1 Set Up the Hosted Database
- Create a new project in your chosen database platform
- Set up collections/collections (e.g., `tasks`, `users`)

#### 3.2 Update Backend (if applicable)
- Replace file I/O logic with database calls
- Example (Node.js + MongoDB):
```js
// Before (local JSON)
const fs = require('fs');
const tasks = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('tasks.json'));

// After (MongoDB)
const { MongoClient } = require('mongodb');
const client = new MongoClient('mongodb+srv://...');

async function getTasks() {
  const db = client.db('taskManager');
  const tasks = await db.collection('tasks').find().toArray();
  return tasks;
}
```

#### 3.3 Migrate Existing Data
- Write a **migration script** to read from local JSON and insert into the database

Example (Node.js):
```js
const fs = require('fs');
const { MongoClient } = require('mongodb');

async function migrateTasks() {
  const client = new MongoClient('mongodb+srv://...');
  await client.connect();

  const db = client.db('taskManager');
  const collection = db.collection('tasks');

  const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('tasks.json'));
  await collection.insertMany(data);

  console.log('Migration complete.');
  await client.close();
}

migrateTasks();
```

> **Note**: Adjust this script based on your actual JSON structure and database schema.

